                <h4 id="basics">Basics</h4>

                    <p>Cryptography is a foundational concept in the realm of information security. At its core, it involves the practice of transforming <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Original Data" style="color: #a324fe;">plaintext</span> into <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Encrypted Data" style="color: #a324fe;">ciphertext</span> using various mathematical algorithms and cryptographic keys. </p>

                    <p>The primary objective of cryptography is to ensure that sensitive information remains confidential and secure, even when transmitted or stored in potentially insecure environments. The field of cryptography extends beyond confidentiality to include other critical aspects such as 
                    <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Guarding against improper information modification" style="color: #a324fe;">integrity</span>,
                    <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Validating origins of files trhough proof of identity" style="color: #a324fe;">authenticity</span>, and <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title=" Adhering to an legal obligation " style="color: #a324fe;">non-repudiation</span>.</p>

                    <p>Early <span style="color: #e12f2f">ciphers</span> serve as a crucial part of the cryptographic heritage, providing historical context, foundational principles, and inspiration for innovation in modern cryptography. While modern cryptographic techniques have advanced significantly, the study of early ciphers remains essential to understanding the rich history and ongoing evolution of the field.</p>
