                <!-- ciphers -->
                <h4 id="ciphers"><i class="fa-regular fa-font-awesome" style="color: #dc3545;"></i> Ciphers</h4>

                    <p>Ciphers, sometimes known as 'old-school ciphers', refer to historical encryption methods used in ancient times or before 'modern' cryptographic techniques. These ciphers often rely on simple and easily understood principles.</p>
                    <p>Here are some key principles commonly associated:</p>

                    <ul>
                        <li><span style="color: #e12f2f">Substitution</span>: Wherein each letter or symbol in the plaintext is replaced with another letter or symbol. Notable examples include the <span style="color: #e12f2f">Caesar Cipher</span>.</li>
                        <li><span style="color: #e12f2f">Transposition</span>: These ciphers involve rearranging the order of characters in the plaintext without changing the characters themselves.</li>
                        <li><span style="color: #e12f2f">Monoalphabetic</span>: Involves the use of a single substitution rule for each character, making them relatively easy to break through <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="The study of the frequency of letters or groups of letters in a ciphertext" style="color: #a324fe;">frequency analysis</span>.</li>
                        <li><span style="color: #e12f2f">Polyalphabetic</span>: The usage ofmultiple substitution rules based on the position of the character in the plaintext or a keyword, adding complexity to the encryption process. The most known of these is the <span style="color: #e12f2f">Vigen√®re cipher</span>.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>Many old school ciphers rely on the use of secret keys to control the encryption and decryption processes. These keys determine the specific substitution or transposition rules applied during encryption. While old school ciphers lack the security features of modern encryption techniques, they remain essential for understanding the principles upon which modern cryptographic methods are built.</p>
