                <!-- Sym -->
                <h4 id="symmetrical"><i class="fa-regular fa-font-awesome" style="color: #0dcaf0;"></i> Symmetrical</h4>

                    <p>Symmetric algorithms are a class of cryptographic algorithms used to encrypt and decrypt data, and they are called "symmetric" because the same key is used for both encryption and decryption.In this type of encryption, the sender and receiver must share a <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Series of bits used to encrypt and decrypt information" style="color: #a324fe;">secret key</span>.</p>

                    <p>Symmetric algorithms are known for their speed and efficiency, making them suitable for scenarios where performance is critical. However, <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="The transport of a key between two indivudals" style="color: #a324fe;"> key distribution </span> can be a challenge, as both parties need to securely exchange and manage the secret key.</p>
                    <p>Improper management of encryption keys is a common problem, and a poor key management system can have a number of negative effects, including increased likelihood of a <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Security incident where unauthorized parties gain access to sensitive data or confidential information" style="color: #a324fe;">data breach</span>.</p>

                    <p>Symmetric algorithms are popular for several reasons, making them a preferred choice for many cryptographic applications:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <span style="color: #0dcaf0"> <i class="bi bi-award"></i>Versatile</span>: Symmetric algorithms are versatile and can be used in various cryptographic applications, including data encryption, file encryption, disk encryption, and more. Their adaptability makes them suitable for a wide range of security requirements and scenarios.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span style="color: #0dcaf0"><i class="bi bi-file-lock"></i>Secure </span>:
                            Many symmetric algorithms have been rigorously studied and tested over the years, resulting in a strong body of knowledge about their security properties and vulnerabilities. Algorithms like the <span style="color: #0dcaf0">Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) </span> are widely recognized for their resilience against known attacks when used with appropriate key lengths.
                        </li>
                    </ul>


