                <!-- Asym -->
                <h4 id="asymmetrical"><i class="fa-regular fa-font-awesome" style="color: #ffc107;"></i> Asymmetrical </h4>

                    <p>Asymmetric algorithms, also known as <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Method of encrypting or signing data with two different keys and making one of the keys, the public key, available for anyone to use" style="color: #a324fe;">public-key cryptography </span>, are a fundamental class of cryptographic techniques that use two different but <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Sharing a mathematical origin" style="color: #a324fe;">mathematically related</span> keys: a public key and a private key. </p>
                    
                    <p>These keys are generated as a pair, and each key serves a distinct purpose in the encryption and decryption processes. Asymmetric cryptography addresses key distribution challenges present in symmetric cryptography by allowing users to share their public keys openly while keeping their private keys secret</p>
                    <p>In asymmetric cryptography:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            The <span style="color: #ffc107">Public Key </span>is used for encryption, and anyone can use it to encrypt data intended for the owner.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            The <span style="color: #ffc107">Private Key </span>is only kept by the owner who can decrypt and access the original data.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>This fundamental principle of asymmetric encryption enables secure communication and data exchange without the need for a shared secret key. Asymmetric algorithms play a crucial role in securing modern communications and online transactions.</p>

                    <p>They are however, less commonly used in some specific contexts due to certain characteristics and performance considerations, with following reasons including:</p> 
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <span style="color: #ffc107"> <i class="bi bi-calculator-fill"></i>Computational Complexity </span>: These algorithms are
                            <span class="keyword" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="Requires intensive mathematical calculations to be done by the computer" style="color: #a324fe;
                            ">computationally intensive</span>. Operations involving large prime numbers and mathematical functions are inherently slower than the simpler bit operations used in symmetric cryptography. This makes asymmetric algorithms less suitable for tasks that require high-speed encryption and decryption.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span style="color: #ffc107"><i class="bi bi-key"></i>Key Size </span>:
                            Public and private keys in asymmetric cryptography tend to be larger than symmetric keys. This can be a disadvantage in situations where memory and storage are limited like in mobile applications.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    
